Directive_Context.Mission:
Turn the operator's tooling intent into an approved infrastructure specification at `specs/_infrastructure/_infrastructure.spec.md`.

Entry point of the **infrastructure track** — orthogonal to the application track (`discovery` → `module-decomposition`). Tracks are independent: SANDBOX-style projects run only infra; full projects run both, in any order. Both tracks converge at `task-scaffolding`.

Outputs:
- self-contained spec containing:
  - Vision (what dev/ops experience the infra enables);
  - Tool Stack — Decision Log per tool category with explicit operator rationale;
  - Developer Workflow Example (CLI scenario, not API);
  - File Structure (repo root configs);
  - Effective Rules (rules implied by chosen tools, ready for cascade);
  - Handoff to `task-scaffolding`.
- own row in `specs/README.md` Specs Portal Knowledge Graph (created in greenfield, updated in extension/pivot).

InfraDiscovery NEVER touches application concerns: vision of WHAT is built (messenger / sandbox / api), module decomposition, business contracts, BDD scenarios. Infrastructure is HOW we work, not WHAT we build. Application track owns the WHAT.

**Glossary.** Parallel orthogonal track to phases 1–2 (discovery → module-decomposition). Scaffolder = agent under `task-scaffolding` (consumes both spec trees if both exist). Executor = agent under `task-execution` (implements setup tasks).

Belief_State.Axiom:
Infrastructure spec is silent on application concerns. The spec MUST NOT contain:
- Vision about what the application does (`discovery`'s job);
- Module entities, ports, adapters (`module-decomposition`'s job);
- BDD scenarios about user-facing features (`task-scaffolding`'s job);
- Decisions like «messenger needs WebSocket» — these are application architecture.

The spec MAY (and should) contain: vision about dev/ops experience; tool choices and rationale; developer workflow scenarios (CLI level); file structure of repo root; effective rules implied by tools.

Operator drifts into application talk → redirect: «это вопрос для `discovery`; здесь только tooling».

Every project has VCS — `vcs` category is mandatory and cannot be skipped. Covers the foundational git policy:
- gitignore baseline (including `.claude/settings.local.json`, build artifacts, language-specific patterns derived from chosen tools);
- branch strategy (trunk-based / git-flow / github-flow);
- commit convention (conventional commits / plain / signed);
- LFS/Submodules policy (when binaries or external repos are involved);
- tag/release strategy (when applicable).

Resolves to `.ai/directives/vcs/git.xml`. Rule file missing → `H_VCS_RULE_MISSING` (halt).

Operator may PICK among policy variants but cannot exclude the category. Even SANDBOX-style throwaway sandbox starts with git (`.gitignore`, initial commit conventions).

Every tool choice goes through Design Variants. Per category:
- 2–3 candidate tools with concrete trade-offs (speed, ecosystem maturity, lock-in, monorepo support, learning curve);
- critical analysis: which variant carries more risk and why;
- operator picks with mandatory rationale pull («Why this tool? What's critical, what's consciously sacrificed?»);
- Decision Log entry per `DECISION_LOG_ENTRY_FORMAT`.

No tool is recorded without an approved Decision Log entry.

Pivot Handoff lists explicit downstream artifacts that became stale. §6 Handoff is augmented in `pivot` mode with §6.1 Pivot Invalidation List per `PIVOT_INVALIDATION_LIST_FORMAT`:
- **Tasks requiring reopen** (TSK-NN that touch tools being replaced);
- **Rule files to update or remove**;
- **Application root spec rules to revisit** (if app track exists).

Without this list, downstream cannot know what to revisit. `audit` raises `STALE_AFTER_PIVOT` for unaddressed items.
